## Prompt A

Before this module, I assumed AI was already becoming a permanent part of higher education and that most discussions had shifted from whether we should use it to how we should use it responsibly. After reading and completing the exploration activities, I still largely hold that view. What the module complicated for me was the distinction between foundation models, large language models, and generative AI. Those terms are often used interchangeably in public conversations, but they describe different things. I also found the discussion of foundation models helpful because it explained why current AI systems feel different from earlier generations of AI tools.

## Prompt B

I was not particularly surprised by the technical content of this module because I have been following developments in AI and using these tools regularly for several years. What I found myself reflecting on instead was how different current AI systems feel from earlier generations. Before the release of modern foundation models, tools such as Google's search and AI-assisted features often felt more accurate because they were narrower in scope and more directly tied to identifiable sources. Current large language models are significantly more flexible and capable, but that flexibility can sometimes create a false sense of confidence. They are often able to generate persuasive explanations even when they are wrong. This matters in my work because I frequently use AI to summarize information, draft communications, and brainstorm ideas. The challenge is no longer whether the tool can produce an answer, but whether I have enough expertise to evaluate the answer it gives.

## Prompt C

One task I perform regularly is creating training materials and educational content for undergraduate researchers and mentors across multiple institutions. Based on what I learned, summarization and content generation capabilities could significantly reduce the time required to draft materials, generate examples, or adapt content for different audiences. At the same time, the module reinforced the need to review outputs carefully. AI can help organize information and create first drafts, but accuracy, context, and audience appropriateness still require human judgment. I see AI as a tool that can reduce the time spent on routine content development while allowing more time for program design and relationship-building.
